Q:

how to call my jquery function on dynamically generated html (by jquery)

I have a script (script in footer) which generates a div with random content from a database.
This div is generated by the following function:
function randomContent() {
    $.get('getContent.php', function (data) {
        var content = $('.dynamicContent').html(data);
        //$(content).find('p').before('random content: <br/>');

    });
}

I wanna use that content inside another function, to change the content of a div (which is generated by jQuery before) based on the new content. The new script:
$('#dynamicContent, #dynamicContent1').html('<p>' + content += '</p>');

How do i add my function content += to the dynamically generated content?
Thanks :)

A:

Don't know what content += is, but you can just do the following (this requires the data variable to be a string):
var newContent = data + content;

The + will concatenate strings, and the = will append new content to the variable with the name defined in the variable.
What's happening is that PHP is returning the html for the div with the class.dynamicContent as a string (the data variable), but your current function is just taking that string of code and placing it in a variable.  So, when it comes to jQuery, that variable isn't getting to anything.

